\subsection{\textit{evaporationPot}}
Module evaporationPot.py calculates potential evapotranspiration if this is required. In our case this will be supplied by another model. Module evaporation.py calculates reference evaportranspiration for the various land cover types using a crop factor. \\

\subsection{\textit{waterdemand}}
The model calculates industrial, domestic and irrigative water demands. Demand is computed as a uniform depth within a pixel. The attribute self.var.InvArea ($= 1 / self.var.cellArea$) is used in waterdemand.py to mean the minimum depth that is counted towards demand; depths below this value are rounded down to zero. In waterbalance.py, water volumes are multipled by self.var.InvArea to get a depth (i.e. effectively dividing by the cell area). 

\subsubsection{Industrial and domestic demand}
Gross and net industrial and domestic water demands are pre-calculated and supplied as NetCDF input files (one file for gross demand, another for net demand). 

\subsubsection{Irrigation demand}
Irrigation demand is calculated for paddy and non-paddy crops. Following \citet{wada_global_2014}, flood irrigation over paddy is represented as a 50mm deep pond that is maintained from the start of the growing season until 20 days prior to the harvest date. The variable self.var.irrGrossDemand is an array with up to four elements, but the only indices used are 2 (paddy) and 3 (non-paddy) (N.B. I \textit{think} this may be so the indices correspond with the index when they are considered with non-irrigated land use types). Paddy irrigation water demand is calculated with the equation:

\begin{verbatim}
self.var.irrGrossDemand[No] = np.where(self.var.cropKC[No] > 0.75, np.maximum(0., (self.var.alphaDepletion * self.var.maxtopwater - (self.var.topwater + self.var.availWaterInfiltration))), 0.)
\end{verbatim}

\noindent where self.var.cropKC is the crop coefficient, self.var.alphaDepletion is..., self.var.maxtopwater is the maximum depth of flood water on a paddy field, self.var.topwater is the current depth of water and self.var.availWaterInfiltration is water available for infiltration ($= throughfall + snowmelt$).

Runoff in CWatM is computed using the modified Arno scheme (TODO: look up reference - Todini, 1996). The irrigation requirement of non-paddy crops is not allowed to exceed infiltration capacity, so the model first calculates the maximum potential infiltration capacity, potInf (Lines 197-205). Next, the program calculates readily available water (readAvlWater) by multiplying the water content minus the wilting point by the root depth in the top two soil layers (Lines 212-215). 

