\subsubsection{Crop water demand}

Following \citet{wada_global_2014}, flood irrigation over paddy is represented as a 50mm deep pond that is maintained from the start of the growing season until 20 days prior to the harvest date. Thus, irrigation water requirement, $IWR_{paddy}$, is calculated

\begin{equation}
  IWR_{paddy}(t) = max(0,S_{max} - (S_{0}(t-1) + P_{eff}(t))
\end{equation}

\noindent where $S_{max}$ is the maximum surface water storage, $S_{0}$ is the initial storage and $P_{eff}$ is effective precipitation. The change in surface water storage, $S$, is calculated as follows:

\begin{equation}
  \frac{dS}{dt} = P_{eff}(t) + IWR_{paddy}(t) - q_{i,S_{0} \rightarrow S_{1}}(t) - E(t)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $q_{i,S_{0} \rightarrow S_{1}}$ is the infiltration from the surface soil layer to the uppermost soil layer (i.e. the root zone) according to the saturated hydraulic conductivity, reduced by a factor of 10 in order to account for compaction \citep{}, and $E$ is the open water evaporation from the paddy field. Direct runoff from paddy fields is neglected because it is assumed that farmers will not irrigate prior to expected rainfall. \\

The irrigation water requirement of non-paddy crops is calculated following the procedure outlined in FAO... , In this formulation, the root zone is conceptualised as a bucket... The volume of water available to crops after the soil has drained to field capacity is called the total available water (TAW)

\begin{equation}
  TAW = (\theta_{FC} - \theta_{WP}) Z_{r}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\theta_{FC}$ and $\theta_{WP}$ are the soil field capacity and wilting point, respectively, and $Z_{r}$ is the rooting depth, which is assumed to increase exponentially during the growing season to the maximum rooting depth. Readily available water (RAW) is the fraction of TAW that can be extracted by crops before they are subject to water stress \citep{mackay_lumped_2014}, such that

\begin{align}
  RAW &= pTAW\\
  p   &= p_{ref} + 40 \times (0.005 - ET_{c})
\end{align}

\noindent where $p$ is the soil water depletion factor and $p_{ref}$ is a reference value which varies according to crop type. Assuming that irrigation is required when root zone depletion $D_{r}$ falls below RAW, the irrigation water demand of a non-paddy crop can be expressed as follows:

\begin{equation}
  IWR_{nonpaddy} =
  \begin{cases}
    D_{r}, & \text{if}\ D_{r} > RAW_{t} \\
    0,    & \text{otherwise.}
  \end{cases}
\end{equation}

The change in water balance of the root zone, expressed in terms of root zone depletion, can be written as:

\begin{equation}
  \frac{dD_{r}}{dt} =  ET_{c} + DP - (P-RO) - CR - I
\end{equation}

\noindent where $ET_{c}$ is actual crop evapotranspiration, $DP$ is percolation to the underlying soil layer, $P$ is precipitation, $RO$ is surface runoff, $CR$ is capillary rise and $I$ is irrigation (all in metres). Crop evapotranspiration is calculated as follows:

\begin{equation}
  ET_{c} = k_{s}k_{c}ET_{0}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $ET_{0}$ is reference evapotranspiration, $k_{c}$ is the crop coefficient and $k_{s}$ is the water stress coefficient. Reference evapotranspiration can be calculated using various methods depending on data availability. The water stress coefficient is calculated as a function of root zone depletion, as follows

\begin{equation}
  k_{s} = \frac{TAW-D_{r}}{(1-p)TAW}.
\end{equation}

\noindent The crop coefficient $k_{c}$ is a time-varying parameter which reflects changes in crop physiology during the growing season. The FAO provide a set of $k_{c}$ values for several crops for initial, ... growth stages, as well as estimates of the length of each stage in days. An alternative method for calculating $k_{c}$ at different time points is use remote sensing data. \\

